<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title></title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Univers; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">PUB0011</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Univers; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Univers; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence from the </span><span style="font-family:Univers; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Office of Fair Trading (OFT</span><span style="font-family:Univers; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">)</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><img src="data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAApQAAAACCAYAAADmb0xLAAAAAXNSR0IArs4c6QAAAARnQU1BAACxjwv8YQUAAAAJcEhZcwAADsMAAA7DAcdvqGQAAAA8SURBVFhH7daxCQAACAPB7L+0FjpB6hPE/vjC5GYsAw1oQAMa0IAGNKCBooF/Jx0CBAgQIECAAAECpcACFGWPjazJYDAAAAAASUVORK5CYII=" width="660" height="2" alt="" style="margin-left:-11.25pt; margin-top:16.95pt; position:absolute; z-index:0" /></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Univers; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction </span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The OFT is grateful for the opportunity to respond to the Public Administration Select Committee’s enquiry into citizens and public services. This response draws on insights from the OFT’s work in public service markets and focuses on the three questions where it has particular experience: questions 3, 8, and 9.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The OFT’s primary aim is to make markets work well for consumers. We pursue this goal by: encouraging businesses to comply with competition and consumer law and to improve their trading practices through self-regulation; acting decisively to stop hardcore or flagrant offenders; studying markets and recommending action where required; and empowering consumers with the knowledge and skills to make informed choices and get the best value from markets.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Given the importance of public services, and the  importance of improving the way in which public services are delivered, public service markets are one of five priorities in the OFT’s Annual Plan for 2013-14.</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> As such, the OFT works constructively with other government departments and public bodies to help them frame and deliver services in a manner that benefits both consumers and taxpayers. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">3. What are the risks and opportunities of opening up public services to alternative forms of ownership, provision and accountability? </span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There are different ways in which competition can be introduced in the provision of public services. Different organisations – public, private and voluntary – can compete for government contracts, engaging in competition ‘for’ the market. Examples of these types of markets include employment support services and probation services. Alternatively, different providers can </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">compete ‘in’ the market by trying to attract individual service users, with rewards being dependent on the number of users they attract as well as other performance variables. This type of competition is increasingly extended in sectors such as healthcare, education and social care. These models can also be mixed. For example in domicilary care, local authorities  often tender for providers to be a preferred or default service provider - negotiating prices on the basis of higher expected volumes – while allowing service users a budget to choose between licensed suppliers.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The introduction of competition in public service markets can result in benefits to service users and the taxpayer. Both models of opening up public services expose providers to competitive pressures. When there is competition ‘for’ the market, providers face the threat that their contracts will be lost to competitors if their performance falls or quality falls below a certain standard. When there is competition ‘in’ the market, providers face the threat that service users (and, therefore, funding) will be lost to competitors if their services do not reflect users’ needs and preferences. Providers therefore face incentives to offer better value for money or risk losing contracts or market share. This competitive pressure, in turn, can generate efficiencies for service users and taxpayers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">.</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">However, the OFT’s work in public service markets highlights that there are challenges that can prevent the opening up of public services from realising these benefits in practice.   </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">When investigating public markets the OFT often finds obstacles which prevent the design and implementation of policy frameworks that effectively embed competition and choice. Challenges can arise from: </span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Factors that restrict the level of provider competition </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Restrictions on competition created by commissioning and procurement practices </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Factors that restrict the extent of consumer empowerment </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ul><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In public service markets, the OFT is also alert to the risk of:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Potential breaches of competition law by public bodies when they engage in ‘economic activity’ </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Factors that restrict the level of provider competition  </span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">For competition to work effectively, incumbent providers need to feel ‘constrained’ by the threat of competition from alternative providers who can enter the market at relatively low cost and win contracts or win service users from incumbents. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">If there are barriers that prevent alternative providers from starting to compete for services, incumbents may be afforded sufficient market power to be able to reduce the quality of services or charge service users or government supra-competitive fees for their services. A provider with a large market share in a market protected by significant entry barriers is likely to have market power. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There are many ways in which entry barriers in public service markets can be categorised, but it is useful to identify the following factors which, depending on the circumstances, can increase barriers to entry into public service markets: </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">•</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">sunk costs (costs that cannot be recovered once an organisation has entered the market), </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">•</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">poor access to key inputs and distribution outlets, </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">•</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">economies of scale, </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">•</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">network effects, </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">•</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">exclusionary behaviour, </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">•</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">regulation.</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In public service markets, as in private markets, policy makers need to be aware of the impact regulations can have on the ability of providers to enter the market and compete. The OFT has identified barriers to entry created by regulation in a number of markets. For example, when the OFT looked at the pharmacy service market in 2003 it found that the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> effect of the control of entry regulations had acted to impede entry and expansion by pharmacies that offered consumers lower prices, more convenient opening times, or valued and innovative services. Moreover, by limiting the numbers and location of pharmacies in a local area, the regulations had restricted competition between pharmacies, in terms of both prices and quality of service.</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The extent to which opening up public services to competition will result in benefits to service users and taxpayers will also depend on the extent to which successful providers are rewarded for their success. In competitive private markets, successful firms make profits and expand. Unsuccessful ones make losses and eventually go out of business or are taken over by their rivals. In the public sector it is often more difficult to design a funding system which rewards success and in turn ‘punishes’ failure. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Barriers to expansion can prevent institutions from being rewarded for success. Schools, for example, get more money for each pupil they take on, but often face physical constraints, such as the size of the school, which can prevent them from increasing how many additional pupils can take on each year. There may also be wider policy considerations that affect the ability and incentive of schools to expand such as the need to have balanced geographical provision. Further, it can be expensive for the government to run a system of public services with the excess capacity needed to allow successful services expand and less successful services shrink. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">If services are opened up to competition without a mechanism through which successful providers can expand and, in turn, less successful providers shrink, the result can be a guaranteed supply of service users and funding to the institutions that are underperforming. There may well be legitimate policy objectives which prevent funding to failing institutions from shrinking further, such as concern for the service users that are left with the failing organisation. However, barriers to expansion and contraction will undermine the basic premise of opening up service provision – that successful providers need to be rewarded both for that success and for competing with each other on the right parameters, so that more end users can collectively benefit from their offering of high quality, innovative, value for money services. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The competitive dynamic can be further undermined if there are barriers which prevent public service providers from ever exiting the market. We explore the issue of provider failure in more detail in our response to question 9. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Specific restrictions on competition created by commissioning and procurement practices</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Given the prevalence of competition ‘for’ the market through commissioning and procurement exercises, it is worth highlighting the particular </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">commissioning and procurement practices which can undermine the competitive process and restrict competition to a small selection of providers. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The OFT's research has highlighted commissioning and procurement in public services markets which can act to disadvantage some suppliers, or even prevent them from participating in the competition process at all.</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In 2011 the OFT identified a number of practices which can exacerbate barriers to entry in public services markets including: </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Overly long and non-standardised Pre-Qualification Questionnaires (PQQs):</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> smaller suppliers may be dissuaded from bidding if the length of time and cost involved in completing PQQs is significant and different for each tender, especially if the chances of success are uncertain.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The frequency of tendering</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">: if the length of contracts is short and retendering is a frequent occurrence, some suppliers may not have sufficient time to recover costs and thus face a barrier to entry (this will also increase bidding costs), but equally overly long contracts can make it harder for some unsuccessful bidders to stay in the market if these contracts are only rarely put out to market, especially when the public sector constitutes a significant buyer in the market.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Requirements to have an extensive track record:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> tender requirements that seek multiple examples of past experience and references can deter potential new entrants who have no track record but an innovative approach, and risk entrenching incumbency advantages enjoyed by either the in-house supplier or existing private or third sector providers.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Such practices can, in turn, can reduce the degree of genuine competition that occurs both over the short-run and long-run and may give incumbent providers sufficient protection from competition that they are able to reduce quality, efficiency or increase prices without losing sales.</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> We would also point to the persistence of informal barriers to entry that can tend to favour incumbent suppliers. These can include things like ‘old tie networks’, or risk aversion on the part of commissioners which will tend to favour incumbent suppliers with established reputations. Reducing barriers to entry and competition requires commissioners of public services to ensure procurement </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">policies and processes do not discriminate against certain types of suppliers, particularly smaller suppliers, and encourage the widest possible participation.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Factors influencing the extent of consumer empowerment </span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">If public services are exposed to competition ‘in’ the market where services users are expected to choose between providers, they need to be able to make informed decisions about the providers that best meet their needs and provide value for money. We explore some of the challenges in service users exercising choice in public services in our response to question 8. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Potential breaches of competition law by public bodies when they engage in ‘economic activity’ </span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In addition to the broad challenges described above which can prevent competition from working effectively, public service providers need to be aware that their functions fall under UK and EU competition law if they are carrying out ‘economic activity’. Further, where public bodies also seek to generate revenues by utilising assets or spare capacity in markets beyond their core public functions they may  come within competition law. Such developments reinforce the need for public bodies to be aware of their existing and ongoing obligations under UK and EU competition law when carrying out their functions. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The OFT has published guidance on when public bodies might be subject to UK and EU competition law.</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> In broad terms, a public body should ask itself the following questions for each of its activities separately: </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt 97.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Am I offering or supplying a good or service, as opposed to, for example, exercising a public power? </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt 97.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">If so, is that offer or supply of a 'commercial' – rather than an exclusively 'social' – nature? </span></li></ul><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">If the answer to both these questions is yes, then – </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">for the purposes of that activity (and any related upstream purchasing) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">– the public body is likely to be regarded as an ‘undertaking’ subject to UK and EU competition law.</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> A p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rofit </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">making motive is not required; non-profit making activities can also be commercial if they are or could be provided by the private sector.</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 14pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The OFT is keen to ensure that, where public bodies do engage in economic activities, a level playing field and a similar commitment to compliance exists for all operators in those markets. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">8. How realistic is it that ‘choice’ can be exercised in public service provision or should be we looking instead at greater control by users so they can ensure that public services become more responsive to changing needs?</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">As described in our response to question 3, one ‘model’ through which public services can be opening up to a greater range of providers is by giving service users the mechanisms through which they can choose the services they think best reflect their needs. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In a well functioning market, active consumers exert pressure on firms to improve their product and service offerings. Informed consumer choice ensures that consumers are more likely to receive services that they need and are less likely to be inefficiently supplied services from which they do not benefit. OFT work has identified a number of benefits in encouraging choice between public service providers including: </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 53.07pt; padding-left:10.73pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The intrinsic value of being able to exercise a choice in services funded by the state. People often appear to value choice for its own sake, independent of any impact it may have on the quality of the service, </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 53.07pt; padding-left:10.73pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Increasing the likelihood that the right services are delivered to the right people, </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 53.07pt; padding-left:10.73pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">As a means of driving improved efficiency and better outcomes, and</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 53.07pt; padding-left:10.73pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Reducing the wider costs to society of poor decision making.</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  </span></li></ul></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63.8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Not all service users need to be able to make informed choices for a market to work effectively. As long as service providers are unable to discriminate between service users on the basis of price and service quality, a core of informed and engaged consumers can drive value for money across the market for all users. However, for a system centred on user choice to work effectively, it is important that a core of service users have the ability to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">‘access, assess and act on’ information to make effective choices. It may be difficult to access, assess or act on information if: </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 53.07pt; padding-left:10.73pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Awareness that a choice exists is limited,</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 53.07pt; padding-left:10.73pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Service users lack confidence or independent guidance in how to exercise choice, and </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 53.07pt; padding-left:10.73pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Choice is based upon measures of quality rather than price. Quality can be can be hard to assess before experiencing the service, may only be understood a long time after the service is provided, and in any case may be difficult to express in objective performance indicators.</span></li></ul></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There may therefore be a number of challenges which, if not addressed, can prevent development of effective choice in public services, including:</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 53.07pt; padding-left:10.73pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">How to raise awareness that service users have a choice and how to help more vulnerable service users to exercise that choice.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 53.07pt; padding-left:10.73pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">How to help consumers make choices between services where quality may be hard to assess, particularly when the services will have a complicated and hard to predict impact on the user’s life. </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Importantly, in most public services the government has an obligation to provide the service to all consumers rather than just profitable groups of consumers.  Ensuring vulnerable groups have access to the information and help they need to make informed choices can be a challenge, particularly if information is only available online or there is a lack of support and guidance to help vulnerable users access information. This may be a particular concern for public policy where equitable access and outcomes are a key policy objective.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Using intermediaries to help consumers make more effective choices </span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Intermediaries can play an important role in bridging information gaps and helping users to navigate between the different choices available to them.</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Intermediaries may be especially useful when services are complex, there are no easily comparable quality metrics and when users lack the confidence to exercise choice on their own. In healthcare, for example, the patient may not fully appreciate what is best for their heath and is unlikely to know as much as their GP about the quality of care available in different settings. GPs can help </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">service users make a more informed choice about what provider would most effectively meet their needs. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">To work effectively, there needs to be an alignment of objectives between intermediaries and service users. Consumers may find it hard to trust intermediaries if they are aware that the intermediaries are receiving commissions for recommending products - they may suspect that this makes the intermediaries' advice biased.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> This does not mean that intermediaries can't be useful in reducing complexity, but it does make it vital that they are seen to act impartially.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">For example, when the OFT looked at the private healthcare market in 2011 we noted the possible emerging trend of the provision of financial incentives to GPs by privately funded healthcare providers (PH) with local market power in order to encourage those GPs to refer patients to the PH provider's facilities.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><a name="_ftnref13"></a><a href="#_ftn13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> We were concerned that this trend might have had the potential to develop as a barrier to new privately funded healthcare providers from entering the market and winning business.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Consumers may also find it difficult to choose between intermediaries in a market, and may not be able to accurately provide information about their own consumption patterns that intermediaries would need in order to provide useful advice. To operate effectively, intermediaries themselves need to have access to the necessary data/information to assist the exercise of choice.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-indent:102pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Using ‘choice tools’ to help consumers make more effective choices </span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Where services are more easily comparable, it might be possible to publish metrics about the services providers’ offer to facilitate the emergence of ‘choice tools’ which can be provided by the public or private sector. The OFT’s work on choice tools highlights that such tools have the potential advantage of helping service users to make more informed choices and incentivising service providers to improve their performance in areas publicised by the choice tool.</span><a name="_ftnref14"></a><a href="#_ftn14">[14]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">However, the development of choice tools can pose a number of challenges and risks. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="36" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It can be difficult to establish a common system of metrics that allow users to compare provider quality. Agreeing a common system of metrics may be difficult if different providers stand to gain or lose according to which information is collected. It can also be difficult to agree how to share the common costs of developing a system of data collection, which may fall differently on different providers. Overcoming these collective action problems often requires a strong state role. It may be easier to collect information from public sector providers where Government is in a stronger position to corral providers. For example, in our market study on Private Healthcare we found the NHS Choices system for comparing the quality of NHS hospitals to be significantly more developed than its private sector equivalent – where some of the collective action problems above were evident.</span><a name="_ftnref15"></a><a href="#_ftn15">[15]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="37" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It can also be difficult to ensure the choice tool is updated with accurate and up-to-date information. This may be the case if poor quality providers lack the incentive to keep accurate or up-to-date information. Further, choice-tools often depend on providers updating information, which may not happen if the tool is not interactive and easy for providers to use. For example, in our dentistry market we found poor awareness and low usage levels of choice tools such as NHS Choices which, in part, was likely to have reflected the difficulty with which dental practices could upload information to the website.</span><a name="_ftnref16"></a><a href="#_ftn16">[16]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="38" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Choice-tools which rely on consumer feedback may be of limited usefulness if the information is poor quality and the feedback lacks validity. Consumer feedback may be particularly important for choice in public services due to the complex nature of the services and the difficulty for the average consumer of interpreting myriad performance data. However, if user-generated data is false or inaccurate then consumers can be misled into using services they would otherwise not have chosen. False feedback will also distort competition as service providers receive incorrect signals about how they are performing against their rivals. The OFT has taken a range of enforcement actions to establish a clear precedent against firms that pay for or create false information. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="39" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The OFT refers the Committee to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Empowering consumers of public services through choice tools</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for a more detailed discussion of the risks that need to be managed when developing choice tools.</span><a name="_ftnref17"></a><a href="#_ftn17">[17]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">9. What safeguards should be in place to deal with service providers who fail to deliver services, or who deliver services of an insufficient quality? </span></p><ol start="40" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In recent years there have been some high profile service failures in public service markets that have been ‘opened up’ to choice and competition. Failures such as the financial failure of Southern Cross Healthcare in 2011 and the service failure of G4S to deliver on its security contract for the Olympic Games have brought into focus the need for government to minimise service disruption when things go wrong. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="41" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There is a risk that government responds to failures in public markets by preventing the exit of providers. The OFT considers that effective competition requires a credible threat that firms which fail to provide their contracted service levels will face the consequence of losing market share and ultimately exiting the market if their performance does not improve.However, this does not mean that the government can simply let providers fail without having any contingency plans in place to minimise the disruption that would be experienced by service users. The closure of services can lead to a short term reduction in quality and, in some cases, may put service users at risk even if the closure of the service is only for a short period of time, which may be deemed unacceptable. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The challenge facing policy makers, regulators and contracting authorities therefore is to facilitate the ‘orderly exit’ of failing providers in a way which protects service users and, where appropriate, ensuring continuity of service whilst preserving the credible threat of exit which is an important driver of competition. The OFT looked at how government can address these challenges in its recent report on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Orderly Exit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref18"></a><a href="#_ftn18">[18]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="43" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Our work on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Orderly Exit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> highlights that a ‘virtuous’ competitive cycle can, in itself, go a long way in reducing the impact of service disruption, to the extent that it encourages a diverse range of successful and robust providers to enter, compete and bear the costs of their own actions in the market. For competition to mitigate the disruption caused by provider exit, a range of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">different providers need to be able to compete and take over in cases of failure. In the social care market, for example, supply is diversified and exit is common. The National Audit Office (NAO) study of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Oversight of user choice and provider </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">competition in care markets</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> concluded that exit or take-over of care homes and domiciliary care providers is a feature of local care markets, and that normally other providers come in to run services with little or no impact on users.</span><a name="_ftnref19"></a><a href="#_ftn19">[19]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> This may be due to low levels of concentration within the market for residential services and the effective management of closures at the local level.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="44" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">However, in some public markets strong competition will not be enough to prevent provider failure from being disruptive. A continuity regime may be needed to facilitate orderly provider exit in markets where the impact of short-term discontinuity of service on users is likely to be high, service supply is needed continuously and provider failure is likely to lead to discontinuity of service. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="45" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">To understand when the government might need to design a continuity regime, the OFT suggests that those who oversee public service markets should ask whether short-term discontinuity will:</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 84.2pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">result in major public harm? (for example, A&amp;E services) </span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 84.2pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">have a knock on impact on other providers delivering essential services? (for example, IT services) </span></li></ul></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="46" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">If the answer to either of these questions is yes then policy makers and regulators may need to design a continuity regime – a way of protecting service users and ensuring services remain available, whilst also facilitating the exit or turnaround of a failing provider. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="47" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In doing so, policy makers need to be aware of potential unintended consequences of designing continuity regimes. Continuity regimes need to protect against the risk of disruption in service provision, not against the risk of provider failure or exit. This is an important distinction if competition is to be maintained. It is also important that continuity regimes avoid distorting the competitive dynamics in the public service market. For example, the designers of continuity regimes need to avoid creating ‘moral hazard’ where providers think they will be supported in cases of failure by the government and therefore do not fully take into account the consequences of their actions.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="48" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Further, over time, circumstances can change so that a continuity regime is no longer needed where it washistorically necessary, for example because of a lack of alternative providers,  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is important therefore that the government’s approach to addressing failure incorporates the capacity to respond to changes in the market. Feedback from providers and periodic reviews of market conditions could help to provide an opportunity to reassess how appropriate a given existing or proposed continuity regime is for current market conditions. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Annex 1: Overview of the tools the OFT uses to achieve its goals </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Enforcement:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> tackling anti-competitive agreements or abuses of a dominant position under the Competition Act 1998 (CA98). </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Market studies: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">analysis of a particular market, or practices across a range of goods and services,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">with the aim of identifying and addressing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">any aspects of market failure from competition issues to consumer detriment and the effect of government regulations. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Mergers: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">obtain and review information relating to merger situations and, where necessary, refer any relevant mergers to the Competition Commission for further investigation if it is felt that it will lead to a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">substantial lessening of competition within any market for goods or services in the UK.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Consumer enforcement:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the OFT has a range of powers to enforce consumer law in order to tackle practices and market conditions that make it difficult for consumers to exercise choice.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Advocacy, and awareness raising:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the OFT’s powers under competition and consumer law gives it a responsibility to provide information and advice to government on competition and consumer issues.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">November 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> More information about the OFT’s mission and tools can be found in Annex 1 and here:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.oft.gov.uk/"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.oft.gov.uk/</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Office of Fair Trading Annual Plan 2013-2014. Available here: </span><a href="http://www.oft.gov.uk/shared_oft/about_oft/annual-plan13-14/OFT1462.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.oft.gov.uk/shared_oft/about_oft/annual-plan13-14/OFT1462.pdf</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> For a discussion of the benefits of competition which can be extended to public service markets see: OFT (2011) Competition and Growth Available here: </span><a href="http://www.oft.gov.uk/shared_oft/economic_research/oft1390.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.oft.gov.uk/shared_oft/economic_research/oft1390.pdf</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> A more detailed discussion of barriers to entry can be found here: </span><a href="http://www.oft.gov.uk/shared_oft/business_leaflets/ca98_guidelines/oft415.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.oft.gov.uk/shared_oft/business_leaflets/ca98_guidelines/oft415.pdf</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> OFT (2003) The control of entry regulations and retail pharmacy services in the UK. Available here: </span><a href="http://www.oft.gov.uk/shared_oft/reports/comp_policy/oft609.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.oft.gov.uk/shared_oft/reports/comp_policy/oft609.pdf</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn6"></a><a href="#_ftnref6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> OFT (2011) Competition and commissioning in the public sector. Available here: </span><a href="http://www.oft.gov.uk/shared_oft/reports/comp_policy/OFT1314.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.oft.gov.uk/shared_oft/reports/comp_policy/OFT1314.pdf</span></a></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_ftn7"></a><a href="#_ftnref7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> The OFT also found that NHS dental contract create barriers to entry and expansion in the dentristry market see OFT (2012) Dentistry: a market study. Available here: </span><a href="http://www.oft.gov.uk/shared_oft/market-studies/Dentistry/OFT1414.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.oft.gov.uk/shared_oft/market-studies/Dentistry/OFT1414.pdf</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn8"></a><a href="#_ftnref8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> OFT (2011) Public bodies and competition law. Available here: </span><a href="http://www.oft.gov.uk/shared_oft/ca-and-cartels/OFT1389.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.oft.gov.uk/shared_oft/ca-and-cartels/OFT1389.pdf</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn9"></a><a href="#_ftnref9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Univers; font-size:9pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Univers; font-size:9pt">Those prohibitions, set out in the Competition Act 1998 (CA98)</span><span style="font-family:Univers; font-size:4pt">3 </span><span style="font-family:Univers; font-size:9pt">and the Treaty on the Functioning of the European Union (TFEU)</span><span style="font-family:Univers; font-size:9pt">4 </span><span style="font-family:Univers; font-size:9pt">apply to the conduct of all '</span><span style="font-family:Univers; font-size:9pt">undertakings</span><span style="font-family:Univers; font-size:9pt">'. </span><span style="font-family:Univers; font-size:9pt">In making this assessment, it is the nature of the particular activity being conducted that is key, not the legal form, or public or private sector status, of the body that carries it out. Thus, a body – including a public body – may be an undertaking (and therefore subject to competition law) in respect of some of its activities, but not others.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn10"></a><a href="#_ftnref10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Univers; font-size:9pt">It is also important to note that this 'functional' approach means that a public body may act as an undertaking – and therefore be subject to competition law – in respect of some of its activities, but not in respect of others</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn11"></a><a href="#_ftnref11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> OFT (2011) Empowering consumers of public services through choice tools. Available here: </span><a href="http://www.oft.gov.uk/shared_oft/reports/consumer_protection/oft1321.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.oft.gov.uk/shared_oft/reports/consumer_protection/oft1321.pdf</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn12"></a><a href="#_ftnref12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> In 2011 the OFT hosted an Active Consumers and Complex Transactions event which explored the role on intermediaries in complex markets. An overview of the discussion can be found here: </span><a href="http://www.oft.gov.uk/news-and-updates/events/active-consumers/opinions/"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.oft.gov.uk/news-and-updates/events/active-consumers/opinions/</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn13"></a><a href="#_ftnref13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> OFT (2011) Private Healthcare Market Study. Available here: </span><a href="http://www.oft.gov.uk/shared_oft/market-studies/OFT1396_Private_healthcare.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.oft.gov.uk/shared_oft/market-studies/OFT1396_Private_healthcare.pdf</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn14"></a><a href="#_ftnref14">[14]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> OFT (2011) Empowering consumers of public services through choice tools. Available here: </span><a href="http://www.oft.gov.uk/shared_oft/reports/consumer_protection/oft1321.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.oft.gov.uk/shared_oft/reports/consumer_protection/oft1321.pdf</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn15"></a><a href="#_ftnref15">[15]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> OFT (2011) Private Healthcare Market Study. Available here: </span><a href="http://www.oft.gov.uk/shared_oft/market-studies/OFT1396_Private_healthcare.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.oft.gov.uk/shared_oft/market-studies/OFT1396_Private_healthcare.pdf</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn16"></a><a href="#_ftnref16">[16]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> OFT (2012) Dentistry: an OFT market study. Available here: </span><a href="http://www.oft.gov.uk/shared_oft/market-studies/Dentistry/OFT1414.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.oft.gov.uk/shared_oft/market-studies/Dentistry/OFT1414.pdf</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn17"></a><a href="#_ftnref17">[17]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> OFT (2011) Empowering consumers of public services through choice tools. Available here: </span><a href="http://www.oft.gov.uk/shared_oft/reports/consumer_protection/oft1321.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.oft.gov.uk/shared_oft/reports/consumer_protection/oft1321.pdf</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn18"></a><a href="#_ftnref18">[18]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> OFT (2012) Orderly Exit: Designing continuity regimes in public markets. Available here: </span><a href="http://www.oft.gov.uk/shared_oft/public-markets/OFT1468.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.oft.gov.uk/shared_oft/public-markets/OFT1468.pdf</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn19"></a><a href="#_ftnref19">[19]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> NAO (2011) Oversight of user choice and competition in care markets. Available here: </span><a href="http://www.nao.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/10121458.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.nao.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/10121458.pdf</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p></body></html>